ratings.question_text: Your level of engagement with the course was:
What is your overall assessment of this course?
The course was well organized to facilitate student learning.
I received clear feedback that improved my learning.
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the level of intellectual challenge of this course was:
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the workload of this course was:

narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Stoichometry, gas laws, thermochem, and lots of other chemistry things
I developed a background in inorganic, general chemistry
Learned a lot of the basics of chemistry.
I learned how to overcome challenges and setbacks to rise up and persevere.
- General chemistry skills
Intro chem course so everything from stoichiometry to thermochemistry to Lewis structures
I learned many of the fundamentals of chemistry as well as basic problem solving skills.
I learned a very good insight of all general chemistry, including orbitals, oxidization, acid-base reactions, etc.
broad introduction to chem
Chemistry basics, from what are elements/mixtures to molecular orbitals and colligative properties. As a first-year, I also learned how to study/take advantage of office hours.
I learned the fundamentals of chemistry at a university level.
I learned a variety of beginner topics in chemistry that I would need in later more advanced chemistry courses.

I learned basic scientific skills specific to chemistry. Moreover, I learned problem-solving and how to work hard, as this was without a doubt the most difficult course I've taken thus far in my academic career.
By taking this course, I have learned to better manage my time and develope better studying habits that are effective for me to do well on exams.
I learned the importance of time management and a voluminous amount of Chemistry.

This course taught me efficient ways to deal with an overwhelming amount of material and workload in an extremely accelerated time frame. Gen Chem deals with a massive load of information that goes far beyond what is taught in high school. As a result, you're forced to begin tackling psets and studying long before they are actually due so that you don't deal with the consequences of a 30-question pset due the night of, or a cumulative four-chapter exam the next day.
General chemistry: thermochemistry, bonding, gas laws, etc.
I gained a really good foundational knowledge of chemistry and the main concepts behind it.
Understanding the basics of physical chemistry, pretty critical to nearly every STEM field.

My knowledge of chemistry was certainly improved. I feel as if I have a very good foundation of chemistry knowledge now, especially as someone not going into chemistry as a major. I had covered some of the topics in high school, but not to so much depth or breadth.
A very strong foundation in chemistry, good study/review skills, good strategies for note taking, and how to properly study for an exam.

I gained immense knowledge on key chemistry concepts as well as the history of some of them. Additionally, the demonstrations on Fridays allowed me to apply my learning to real life scientific techniques.
Basic chemistry concepts
In taking this course, I developed a clear understanding of the foundational concepts of chemistry.
The course goes over the basics (nomenclature, redox, acids/bases, etc) and then dives deep into atomic structure and molecular orbitals.
I learned the basics of chemistry and got much better at learning to study large volumes of material
This course helped me understand a broad scope of General Chemistry from fundamental principles of atomic theory to the basics of organic chemistry.
The fundamentals of chemistry!

I learned and advanced my knowledge of basic chemistry. I learned how to take productive notes and prepare for exams. I also gained a skill of being on top of it and learning from mistakes from the problem sets.

I gained knowledge of the basic concepts in chemistry and learned about the fundamental laws, experiments, and ideas in the field. This knowledge will be key for me as I continue to progress through upper level chemistry classes. I developed skills in many different areas in chemistry, like stoicheometry, thermochemistry, and more. I gained a great foundation for chemistry that will serve me well in my Yale experience and beyond.
I developed a comprehensive understanding of general chemistry concepts. The course was very test-based, so I also developed my study skills and habits.
I learned about a wide range of topics in chemistry and how they could be connected to each other.
Basic chemistry knowledge and problem solving mindsets
I learned various topics on basic chemistry.
Learnt a lot of concepts
Learned alot about chemistry and equations used within the subject along with lots of practice questions to further my understanding
This course provided fundamental knowledge for the natural sciences.
Thourough understanding of general chemistry
Nilay's gen chem was a very good experience for me, giving me a great foundation in chemistry, even far above what I learned in AP chemistry in high school.
It's a good introduction to chemistry. I learned to budget time effectively, as this class took a lot out of me.
Fundamentals of chemistry
Insight and knowledge about functioning of basic chemistry and its place within the world.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: There is a noticeable difference in students who have taken AP Chem and those that haven't and it's hard to keep up
All strengths, Nilay is fantastic and grading was relatively fair
Great introduction to topics and class but can use more mathematical questions.

Weaknesses were that I think it could've been taught better but this was evened out by my strength of the course: the Peer Tutors. They were very helpful because they understood the material and they were only sophomores so they better knew how we think and learn and thus had better ways of explaining concepts to us than TAs, for example, did.

Strengths: Detailed, Intellectually Engaging
Weaknesses: Fast-paced, easy to fall behind, weird notetaking system. (Nilay's a great prof but his handwriting is hard to read)

Some strengths of the course is the amount of support available. There were so many TAs and peer tutors to help facilitate our learning and help us with the problem sets. Some weaknesses was the lack of clarity for exams. The expectations were not always clear as to what was expected from us and this made exams very difficult at times.
The course moves very fast. The midterms are long and there is not enough time given to complete them.
Nilay is an amazing lecturer/I always felt supported throughout my learning.

I really liked the lectures and Nilays teaching style. He was super engaging and made the class applicable to many different topics and majors. I really liked discussion sections as well. I thought the formatting of the course was well structured.

Strengths: I believe I learned a lot of valuable information
weaknesses: the slides were taught fast, and sometimes to was hard to comprehend and keep up with in class.

Strengths: Manageable workload, lots of peer tutor hours, Nilay tries to make the class fun and engaging. 
Weaknesses: Nilay's handwriting is hard to read so reviewing lecture notes is difficult, lecture content was not presented very clearly, Nilay was not very accommodating when the recording system was broken, graders would take off points on exam questions without leaving any comments/corrections, 4 exams was too much (should've just been 3 midterms without the final), final exam was too long.

Strengths: lots of office hours, well aligned with textbook, engaging for 250 person lecture

Weaknesses: always looking for specific trigger/kay words on exams
The professor was absolutely amazing and very engaging.  The course was very interesting and the professor made an effort to have many real world applications when he taught.

I really loved Nilay as a professor. He is definitely a cornerstone of the course and his teaching is one of its strengths. Honestly the course was run really well. I really appreciated that the psets mirrored the exam questions. I cant think of any weaknesses!

I do not think it is clear how much of a workload and learning curve there is. I worked extremely hard in this class and it was based on a curve. While this seems like a good thing, many of the students (more than 2/3 I would argue) have taken upper level chemistry in the past two years (AP Chemistry, IB, etc.) and have seen this material before, therefore making the curve much smaller. This is unfortunate for the people who did not have the opportunity to take any college-level chemistry before coming to Yale, as the content is objectively hard; it is a much easier course for those who have seen this material before. Although Yale offers an advanced chemistry course, many opt into taking the regular version, which is extremely detrimental to the people who are completely new to the material.

Strengths: the amount of in-person help provided through this course, whether thats scheduled discussion sections, TF office hours, review sessions, or peer tutoring hours.  Also the lectures were always recorded. Weaknesses: The class didnt truly incentivize me to go to lecture, and sometimes the lecture recordings were only released at the end of the week.  I also think some concepts were taught in a convoluted way, more complicated than Id been taught in high school.

The material is taught at a good pace and in an effective way for understanding of the course material. One weakness was that there were often problems with the recording, wifi, and other technological issues at the location for the class.
Strengths of the course were the content and Nilay's humor.

This course is very much geared towards students planning on pursuing med school. It is not friendly for students who are simply there as a prerequisite for majors that are not as chemistry-focused. I am an Earth and Planetary Sciences major and found that the exams were comprehensive in a way that seemed gratuitous. I wish that a general chemistry course for non-chem, non-premed students existed.

Strengths: NILAY IS AMAZING. Other strengths include the helpful TAs, the high number of peer tutors and office hours, the short but effective p-sets, the demonstrations/experiments.
Weaknesses: Three midterms, not two. I personally think the third midterm is unnecessary. The discussion sections aren't all that productive.
Nilay was a great instructor and did a really good job making the class feel engaging and exciting.

Strengths: Nilay is an excellent lecture and the course was very engaging. The in-class demonstrations every Friday were a nice way to wrap up what we had learned that week. There's SO many resources and the P-sets are really designed to help you understand the material. Also, the TAs and peer tutors were really cool and helpful!
Weaknesses: The class is structured in a somewhat strange way. Nilay goes through the chapters of the textbook in sequential order, which can cause some confusion.

Strength: Nilay is an engaging and personable lecturer who teaches interesting and fun lectures. Weakness: If you come in with little to no chemistry experience it makes it very hard to grasp the concepts. To improve the course, there could be a more fair grading strategy (ie. drop lowest midterm score, higher midterm score counts more, etc.) to ensure students aren't discouraged by one bad score. It would also be helpful to open a section or tutoring program for students who lack chemistry experience.

It requires a lot of memorization of topics that senior chemistry majors have told me they never used again. This part of the course felt somewhat unnecessary. I think a more full formula sheet, including things such as a list of common polyatomic ions and solubility rules, could be helpful in improving the course.

This course is a great introduction to chemistry. It assumes no background knowledge, but manages to engage a wide range of students and student abilities. It covers lots of different topics, and manages to cover them all in sufficient depth to feel a level of mastery (given an introductory course).

The strengths of the class were its engagement with students (highly aided by the professor) and the substantial support system available at all times of day through peer tutors, TAs, and office hours.

The demonstrations on Fridays were always a highlight. Nilay was also a great professor. The abundance of resources was also really helpful. Achieve was especially helpful in teaching concepts because it gave specific feedback based on incorrect answers.
A strength of this course was having weekly experiments to demonstrate the content that we were learning. A weakness was the difficulty of midterm examinations.

Nilay is a true gem. I, like I'm sure a vast majority of the class, took this as a required prerequisite. I was not excited to take the course, but Nilay made chemistry fun. I learned a lot, and there was plenty of support to go around between Nilay and the fantastic TAs. Despite there being over 100 people in the class, Nilay always felt approachable. One weakness was that I didn't feel the required TA section was particularly beneficial for me.
This course was overall very strong, the only weaknesses could be that the discussion sections werent very helpful

Strengths:
- Many office hours and opportunities interact with TAs and professor
- Review sessions (wish they were earlier) and practice tests
Weaknesses: 
- The order of the course: The course was designed to talk about the basics of atomic theory in unit 4 even though I felt like it would be logical to learn it in Unit 1. It seems like the class is taught in chronological history rather than the logical understanding of general chemistry. 
- Problem sets were not really conducive to learning. A lot more calculations than concepts.

The class was enjoyable however the lecture material never really coincided with the homework or test questions. I can say that I was not the only person feeling this way. Yes, the lecture gave us the basics but lecture material doesn't teach us how to solve a problem. The homework is basically another lecture but instead of reviewing through work, you are teaching yourself items that haven't been covered. 

Grading is something that should also be improved on an exam level and a course level. The exam graders are hypercritical of small details rather than the actual answer which doesn't really make sense. Also, final grading did not align with what was said to students throughout the course of the semester.
My strengths were problem sets and the beginning material. My weakness was the fast speed in the second half of the semester.

Strengths: The tests were written fairly, the TAs were very helpful, there was an amplitude of study resources, the engagement in class was high. 

Weaknesses: some grading on the tests was harsh and somewhat unfair.

Strengths: Nilay was an amazing instructor. He made lectures engaging and usually explained concepts very clearly. Besides the midterms, the weekly workload was very manageable, and the Achieve assignments encouraged learning, not perfection.
Weaknesses/improvements: Three midterms were a bit overwhelming, especially when the last one was less than two weeks before our final exam.

I think that this was a good introductory chemistry course and I was able to keep up despite not taking chemistry in a while. The pacing was good, although I wish we could've gone more in-depth into some of the topics.

Strengths:
Professor Hazari is a very engaging professor, and I enjoyed the lecture style format with the weekly problem sets. 
Weaknesses:
None
OneNote notebook material was awesome - clear and easy to understand; summarizes key points

Strength: each class our professor was engaging snd excited to tesch us. Notes were preplanned and posted on canvas that we could look at before class began

Weakness: only about one practice question would be done in class and not alot of opportunities to ask questions

A strength of this course is the abundant content material and study aids that are provided in preparation for exams. A weakness of this course is the teaching style of the professor where he is mostly reading from the lecture notes--at times, this was not engaging.

Strengths: problem sets were formatted to help you learn, professor is fun
Weaknesses: lecture was very fast and often confusing, had to go back an review topics/notes and do problem sets to understand
The workload both from class lectures, problem sets, and practices exams did not translate to the much, much greater intensity of the tests. That said, it's an engaging and fun class.
Well taught, some lectures were hard to follow however
Good support and resource availability for students.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: ONLY take if required for major
The curve is pretty high, so take the course if you can handle the challenge that is associated with the course.
Yes, if it's a requirement for your major/career goals
Yes, it's a great way to learn about chemistry.
No, it is difficult and gets tiring to constantly put in work but not see the fruits.
- Only take it if you need to.
Yes, it fulfills many prereqs for many different STEM majors and for pre-meds. This is a great course to start with for chemistry and the support you have available will help you get through it.

I would not recommend this course unless you HAVE to take it. It is very stressful, and as someone who didn't have a strong chemistry background prior to taking the class, it was very difficult to learn these concepts for the first time and at this speed. The exams are also brutal.
Yes, if they are thinking of going into the sciences. This is a foundational chemistry course.

I definitely would recommend this course. It was the most engaging that a gen chem class could be, and it was fun to be a part of. For a huge lecture, the class community felt strong, and Nilay was a great teacher.
I would highly recommend this course to another student. It was my favorite class this semester, and Nilay was AMAZING.

No, only if you need it for your major. This is not an interesting or inspiring class, so don't just take it for fun or because you think there's a small chance you might want to be premed. Yale offers much more interesting courses, so only take chem 161 if you need to.

Yes. It's an interesting course and well taught (also a requirement for a ton of STEM majors/premed). All lectures are recorded so you can go to every class or you can go to none.

However, if you took AP chem in high school, don't take this! Take Chem 163.

Yes, it is a perfect introduction to chemistry at a university level and it has a very forgiving curve.  There is a lot of material covered and it is by no means an easy course, but it can be very rewarding depending on the level of effort you want to commit to the course.
Yes! A great introduction to chemistry taught by a great professor!

The only way I would recommend this course is if the person has seen the information before. I spent hours upon hours trying to understand this material. Importantly, I learned it. However, I did not learn it to the extent of the people who have seen this content before and were able to recall and recognize the information. Although I made great progress, it surely was not enough. Because of that, I would not recommend this course to anyone who has not taken higher-level chemistry.
Yes, Id recommend.  If you need this as a prerequisite for STEM majors, Gen Chem is a good sequence.
Yes, I would recommend this course to students who are interested in the field of chemistry, as it develops a good background of the subject in just one semester.
I would recommend this course to another student because it is a necessary course to progress into higher level science courses.
There's really no recommending this course. It is mandatory for many academic courses and thus is a necessary stepping stone.

Honestly, if you're taking it with Nilay, yes. He's the best and he'll make Chemistry so much fun. If you want to have a deeper knowledge of chemistry, also yes. Be advised that the class is full of pre-med students and if you're genuinely excited about the science, you won't find many others with the same enthusiasm as you.

If you've taken AP or IB Chemistry, go to 163.

I think it was a good introduction to chemistry, though you definitely need to be comfortable seeking out help on topics/information that you dont understand (either in the textbook or with office hours).
Yes! It's hardly a walk in the park, but it isn't the worst thing ever.
I would recommend this course if its required for one's major and if they have taken AP Chemistry or equivalent.
Yes, I would. It is a very useful course for anyone in STEM, as it covers many fundamental concepts. The workload isn't that high, and the professor was great.

Definitely. Whether or not you're premed, I think an overall understanding of chemistry is critical. Chemistry rides a nice middle ground between physics and biology and is very satisfying once understood. Plus, the teacher (Nilay) is great, and it is worth taking a class with him.
I would definitely recommend this course to another student because generally I believed the coursework, the exams, and the grading were fair and the professor made the class fun.
I would, for it was a very useful course to take. However, I may recommend Credit/D/Failing the course, if possible.
If you're required to take CHEM 161, ABSOLUTELY take it with Nilay. I genuinely enjoyed the course.
I would absolutely recommend this course to other students perusing stem fields

I would recommend this course if you have to take it. If you want a gut or try out sciences, this is not the class. I would only recommend if you have to take it and if you are a STEM major in natural sciences.
Yes, because I enjoyed this class and learned a lot, along with fun class experiments and a great interactive teacher.
Yes, it's a great introduction to chemistry and you will learn a lot. That being said, if Nilay isn't teaching it, the course might not be as enjoyable.
Yes, especially if Nilay is teaching it.
Yes, I would recommend this course. I learned a lot and found it to be interesting, plus the professor and TAs were very supportive.
Yes. The lecturer was engaging and informative.
yes
Definitely. Professor Hazari is a very engaging professor, and the class is a nice way to learn basic chemistry.
Yes, material and lessons were interesting
Yes, teaches quite a lot of stuff at a pretty fast pace but could be handled
Only if you have to take this for a major requirement, there is alot of work and can be quite challenging
Yes, since this a prerequisite for advanced science courses.
Yes, it is challenging but you can do well if you put the work in
I can wholeheartedly recommend Nilay's gen chem to other students. I learned a lot and loved being in class.
It's great if you need to take chemistry for your major. If not, I would encourage auditing the class so that you can learn about the content without experiencing the stress of exams.
Yes, I would recommend this course to students needing to take intro chemistry
Yes good foundation and interesting topics.
